  "prompt": "What are the main characteristics of a plant cell wall?",
  "response": "The plant cell wall has several key characteristics:\n\n1. Composition\n- Primary component is cellulose (a complex carbohydrate)\n- Contains other polysaccharides like hemicellulose and pectin\n- Includes structural proteins and lignin in some cell types\n\n2. Structure\n- Rigid and strong\n- Multi-layered (primary and secondary cell walls)\n- Provides structural support and protection\n- Allows cell shape maintenance\n\n3. Functions\n- Provides mechanical strength\n- Prevents cell from bursting under high internal pressure\n- Controls cell and organism growth\n- Offers protection against pathogens\n- Helps in cell-to-cell communication\n\n4. Physical properties\n- Permeable to water and small molecules\n- Relatively thick compared to animal cell membranes\n- Flexible but strong\n- Can expand during cell growth\n\n5. Chemical characteristics\n- Negatively charged\n- Hydrophilic\n- Capable of chemical modifications\n- Can interact with external environment\n\n6. Developmental aspects\n- Forms during cell division\n- Changes composition during plant growth and differentiation\n\nThese characteristics make the plant cell wall crucial for plant survival and functionality.",
